      {
        "number": 4,
        "title": "The word 'nevertheless' — the anatomy of unbelief at Kadesh",
        "range": "13:26-29",
        "excerpt": "It certainly does flow with milk and honey, and this is its fruit. Nevertheless, the people who live in the land are strong.",
        "body": "The report to the congregation at Kadesh (13:26-29) is the chapter's theological center and the hinge of Israel's history. The structure of the report is simple but devastating: affirmation of the promise confirmed (13:27), then the word *ephes* — 'nevertheless, but, howbeit, only' — followed by every obstacle the spies have catalogued (13:28-29).\n\nThe word *ephes* is Numbers 13's most consequential single syllable. It is not a neutral adversative; it functions as a rhetorical reversal — everything before it is now being systematically overridden by everything after it. The spies do not dispute that the land flows with milk and honey. They dispute that this fact is actionable. They have taken God's gift-declaration and subordinated it to a military assessment. The land is wonderful; the people in it are stronger than Israel; therefore the land is effectively unavailable. This is the logic of *ephes*.\n\nThe obstacles the ten name are real: the cities are fortified (13:28), the Anakim are present (13:28), the full range of Canaanite peoples — Amalekites, Hittites, Jebusites, Amorites, Canaanites — occupy every zone of the land (13:29). The ten spies do not lie about the terrain. Their error is one of omission: they omit the Giver. The report in 13:27-29 does not contain the word God, LORD, or any reference to divine promise. God's name is absent from a report about land He has already declared given. That absence is the unbelief.\n\nHoward Hendricks in *Living by the Book* observes that the most dangerous biblical errors are often not additions to the text but subtractions from it. The ten spies demonstrate his point precisely: they deliver a factually accurate report from which the most important fact — God's promise — has been removed. What remains is technically true and theologically catastrophic.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Ephes* (אֶפֶס) — a strong adversative particle meaning 'only, but, howbeit.' It appears in Amos 9:8 ('I will not totally destroy the house of Jacob, *however*...') with the same function: partially affirming and then overriding. Its use here is the spies' own grammar of unbelief."
      },
      {
        "number": 5,
        "title": "Two verdicts — Caleb's faith and the ten's grasshopper theology",
        "range": "13:30-33",
        "excerpt": "We should by all means go up and take possession of it, for we will surely overcome it. But the men who had gone up with him said, We are not able.",
        "body": "The final four verses stage one of Scripture's starkest theological confrontations. Caleb silences the already-frightened crowd and issues a counter-verdict: 'We should by all means go up and take possession of it, for we will surely overcome it' (13:30). The ten immediately reply: 'We are not able to go up against the people, for they are too strong for us' (13:31). Two verdicts, two frameworks, one set of facts.\n\nCaleb's confidence is grounded in the divine declaration of 13:2. He does not argue that the Anakim are smaller than they appear or that the fortifications are weaker than reported. He argues that the land is given — and when God gives, the receiving is possible regardless of the obstacle profile. His statement 'we will surely overcome it' uses the infinitive absolute for emphasis (*yakhol nuchal lah*) — the grammar of certainty, not wishful thinking. This is what Spurgeon called 'faith that brings the promise into the present' — treating a future divine act as already secured by divine character.\n\nThe ten's counter-report escalates in two ways that reveal the psychology of unbelief. First, the data is exaggerated: the Anakim become Nephilim (13:33), invoking the pre-flood giants of Genesis 6:4. The Anakim were large; calling them Nephilim was a theological inflation designed to make the obstacle cosmically insurmountable. Joshua 11:21-22 reports that Caleb later drove out these same Anakim from Hebron without any such mythological freight — the Nephilim inflation was fear's fabrication, not intelligence reporting. Second, the self-image collapses: 'we became like grasshoppers in our own sight' (13:33). This is the logical terminus of God-excluding reasoning. Remove the Giver from the equation and grasshopper is the accurate self-assessment of a former slave-nation facing giant-defended fortified cities.\n\nThe claim 'so we were in their sight' (13:33) reveals fear's ultimate move: it generates its own confirming data. The ten spies have no way of knowing how the Canaanites perceived Israel. They project the grasshopper self-image outward, manufacturing evidence they cannot possess. This is what John Owen called 'the mind's faculty of self-justifying its own unbelief' — fear does not merely distort perception; it creates the evidence that seems to confirm its distortions.\n\nThe narrator's verdict in 13:32 uses *dibbah* — slander, defamatory whispering. This is not a neutral word for 'report.' It is the same term used in Genesis 37:2 when Joseph brought a bad report (dibbah) about his brothers to their father. The ten spies did not merely assess poorly; they defamed what God had declared good. The narrator refuses the reader any comfortable neutrality: the bad report is named moral, not merely mistaken.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Dibbah* (דִּבָּה) — slander, whispered defamation. *Nephil* (נָפִיל) from *naphal* — to fall; the fallen ones. Used only in Genesis 6:4 and here in the entire Old Testament. The ten spies invoke the most terrifying pre-flood figures available to them. *Chagav* (grasshopper) — a locust-type insect, symbol of insignificance and fragility (cf. Isaiah 40:22 where God sees the nations as *chagav*)."
      }
